{"title_page": "Willem Jacob van de Graaf", "text_new": "{{Infobox governor\n|honorific-prefix   = \n|name               = Willem Jacob van de Graaf\n|honorific-suffix   = \n|image              = \n|alt                = \n|order              = 35th\n|office             = Governor of Dutch Ceylon\n|term_start         = 7 February 1785\n|term_end           = 15 July 1794\n|lieutenant         = \n|predecessor        = [[Pierre Andr\u00e9 de Suffren de Saint Tropez]]\n|successor          = [[Johan Van Angelbeek]]\n|birth_date         = <!-- {{Birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} or {{Birth-date and age|Month DD, YYYY}} -->\n|birth_place        = \n|death_date         = 10 December 1804\n|death_place        = \n|restingplace       = \n|restingplacecoordinates = \n|birthname          = \n|citizenship        = \n|nationality        = \n|party              = \n|otherparty         = <!--For additional political affiliations-->\n|spouse             = \n|partner            = <!--For those with a domestic partner and not married-->\n|relations          = \n|children           = \n|residence          = \n|alma_mater         = \n|occupation         = \n|profession         = \n|cabinet            = \n|committees         = \n|portfolio          = \n|religion           = \n|signature          = \n|signature_alt      = \n|website            = \n|footnotes          = \n<!--Military service-->\n|nickname           = \n|allegiance         = \n|branch             = \n|serviceyears       = \n|rank               = \n|unit               = \n|commands           = \n|battles            = \n|awards             = \n}}\n'''Willem Jacob van de Graaf''' (28 May 1736 or 1737, [[Huissen]] - 10 December 1804, [[Utrecht (city)|Utrecht]]) was the 35th [[List of governors of Dutch Ceylon| Dutch Governor of Ceylon]] during the [[Dutch period in Ceylon]]. \n[[File:Eglise protestante Wolfendhal Street (6).JPG|thumb|left|Ex voto en m\u00e9moire de Lady Christina Elisabeth Ange Heek \u00e9pouse de William Jacob de Graaff.- Colombo]]\nWillem Jacob was the third child of Sebastiaan van de Graaf, Major of Cavalry in the Army of the United Provinces, and Geertruid van Vinceler. At the age of 18, Van de Graaf left on the ship ''Blijdorp'' for Ceylon, where he became a merchant in [[Galle]]. There, in 1862, he married Agnita Clara Samlant (1745-1773), the daughter of the Commander of Galle and Mat. They had five children. In 1766 he became \"head of the Mahabadde\" in [[Colombo]], the civil servant in charge of the economically important cinnamon cultivation. After the death of his first wife, he married Christina Elisabeth van Angelbeek (1756-1792), with whom he had 11 children, two sons and one daughter of which survived childhood.<ref>J. Lever, 1999, [http://www.oud-gorcum.nl/index.php?page=shop.product_details&product_id=664&flypage=flypage.tpl&pop=0&option=com_virtuemart&Itemid=4 Gorkumse geslachten VOC en Ceylon (18de eeuw)], Oud Gorcum Varia, 16, pp. 9-30</ref>\n\nHe was appointed Governor of Ceylon on 7 February 1785 until he was requested in 1793 to become first Counsellor and Director-General of the Dutch Settlement in India (in [[Suratte]]). On 15 July 1794 he was succeeded as governor by his father-in-law, [[Johan van Angelbeek]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Cahoon|first=Ben|title=Dutch Governors|url=http://www.worldstatesmen.org/Sri_Lanka.html|publisher=Worldstatesmen|accessdate=1 March 2013}}</ref> He retired to the estate ''De Liesbosch'' south of the city Utrecht, where he died in 1804.<ref>G.H.P. de Waard, [http://www.museumwarsenhoeck.nl/media/files/1988---Van-buitenplaats-tot-steenbakkerij--De-Liesbosch.pdf Van buitenplaats tot steenbakkerij - de histoie van De Liesbosch]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-gov}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Pierre Andr\u00e9 de Suffren de Saint Tropez]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of Governors of Zeylan|Governor of Zeylan]]|years=1785-1794}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Johan van Angelbeek]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Governors of Zeylan}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Graaf, Willem Jacob van de}}\n[[Category:1737 births]]\n[[Category:1804 deaths]]\n[[Category:18th-century Dutch people]]\n[[Category:18th-century Dutch colonial governors]]\n[[Category:Governors of Dutch Ceylon]]\n[[Category:People from Lingewaard]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox governor\n|honorific-prefix   = \n|name               = Willem Jacob van de Graaf\n|honorific-suffix   = \n|image              = \n|alt                = \n|order              = 35th\n|office             = Governor of Dutch Ceylon\n|term_start         = 7 February 1785\n|term_end           = 15 July 1794\n|lieutenant         = \n|predecessor        = [[Pierre Andr\u00e9 de Suffren de Saint Tropez]]\n|successor          = [[Johan Van Angelbeek]]\n|birth_date         = <!-- {{Birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} or {{Birth-date and age|Month DD, YYYY}} -->\n|birth_place        = \n|death_date         = 10 December 1804\n|death_place        = \n|restingplace       = \n|restingplacecoordinates = \n|birthname          = \n|citizenship        = \n|nationality        = \n|party              = \n|otherparty         = <!--For additional political affiliations-->\n|spouse             = \n|partner            = <!--For those with a domestic partner and not married-->\n|relations          = \n|children           = \n|residence          = \n|alma_mater         = \n|occupation         = \n|profession         = \n|cabinet            = \n|committees         = \n|portfolio          = \n|religion           = \n|signature          = \n|signature_alt      = \n|website            = \n|footnotes          = \n<!--Military service-->\n|nickname           = \n|allegiance         = \n|branch             = \n|serviceyears       = \n|rank               = \n|unit               = \n|commands           = \n|battles            = \n|awards             = \n}}\n'''Willem Jacob van de Graaf''' (28 May 1736 or 1737, [[Huissen]] - 10 December 1804, [[Utrecht (city)|Utrecht]]) was the 35th [[List of governors of Dutch Ceylon| Dutch Governor of Ceylon]] during the [[Dutch period in Ceylon]]. \n[[File:Eglise protestante Wolfendhal Street (6).JPG|thumb|left|Ex voto en m\u00e9moire de Lady Christina Elisabeth Ange Heek \u00e9pouse de William Jacob de Graaff.- Colombo]]\nWillem Jacob was the third child of Sebastiaan van de Graaf, Major of Cavalry in the Army of the United Provinces, and Geertruid van Vinceler. At the age of 18, Van de Graaf left on the ship ''Blijdorp'' for Ceylon, where he became a merchant in [[Galle]]. There, in 1862, he married Agnita Clara Samlant (1745-1773), the daughter of the Commander of Galle and Mat. They had five children. In 1766 he became \"head of the Mahabadde\" in [[Colombo]], the civil servant in charge of the economically important cinnamon cultivation. After the death of his first wife, he married Christina Elisabeth van Angelbeek (1756-1792), with whom he had 11 children, two sons and one daughter of which survived childhood.<ref>J. Lever, 1999, [http://www.oud-gorcum.nl/index.php?page=shop.product_details&product_id=664&flypage=flypage.tpl&pop=0&option=com_virtuemart&Itemid=4 Gorkumse geslachten VOC en Ceylon (18de eeuw)], Oud Gorcum Varia, 16, pp. 9-30</ref>\n\nHe was appointed Governor of Ceylon on 7 February 1785 until he was requested in 1793 to become first Counsillor and Director-General of the Dutch Settlement in India (in [[Suratte]]). On 15 July 1794 he was succeeded as governor by his father-in-law, [[Johan van Angelbeek]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Cahoon|first=Ben|title=Dutch Governors|url=http://www.worldstatesmen.org/Sri_Lanka.html|publisher=Worldstatesmen|accessdate=1 March 2013}}</ref> He retired to the estate ''De Liesbosch'' south of the city Utrecht, where he died in 1804.<ref>G.H.P. de Waard, [http://www.museumwarsenhoeck.nl/media/files/1988---Van-buitenplaats-tot-steenbakkerij--De-Liesbosch.pdf Van buitenplaats tot steenbakkerij - de histoie van De Liesbosch]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-gov}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Pierre Andr\u00e9 de Suffren de Saint Tropez]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of Governors of Zeylan|Governor of Zeylan]]|years=1785-1794}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Johan van Angelbeek]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Governors of Zeylan}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Graaf, Willem Jacob van de}}\n[[Category:1737 births]]\n[[Category:1804 deaths]]\n[[Category:18th-century Dutch people]]\n[[Category:18th-century Dutch colonial governors]]\n[[Category:Governors of Dutch Ceylon]]\n[[Category:People from Lingewaard]]\n", "name_user": "Jcoolbro", "label": "safe", "comment": "Counsillor->Counsellor -Fix a typo in one click", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Willem_Jacob_van_de_Graaf"}
{"title_page": "Spartan C4", "text_new": "<!-- This article is a part of [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Aircraft]]. Please see [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Aircraft/page content]] for recommended layout. -->\n{|{{Infobox Aircraft Begin\n | name=Spartan C4\n | image=File:Spartan C4-225.jpg\n | caption=\n}}{{Infobox Aircraft Type\n | type=Four-seat cabin monoplane\n | national origin=United States\n | manufacturer=[[Spartan Aircraft Company]]\n | designer=\n | first flight=1930\n | introduced=\n | retired=\n | status=\n | primary user=\n | number built=7\n | developed from= \n | variants with their own articles=\n | developed into= [[Spartan C5]]\n}}\n|}\n\nThe '''Spartan C4''' is an [[United States|American]] four-seat cabin monoplane designed and built by the [[Spartan Aircraft Company]].<ref name=\"Orbis\" />\n\n==Design and development==\nThe first model was the C4-225 a high-wing braced monoplane powered by a 225&nbsp;hp (168&nbsp;kW) [[Wright J-6]] radial engine.<ref name=\"Orbis\" /> Only five C4-235 aircraft were built and they were followed by one C4-300 with a 300&nbsp;hp (224&nbsp;kW) [[Wright R-975]] radial engine, and the C4-301 with a 300&nbsp;hp (224&nbsp;kW) [[Pratt & Whitney Wasp Junior]].<ref name=\"Orbis\" />\n\n==Variants==\n;C4-225\n:Production aircraft powered by a 225hp (168kW) [[Wright J-6]] radial engine, five built.<ref name=\"Orbis\">Orbis 1985, p 2955</ref>\n;C4-300\n:Variant with a 300hp (224kW) [[Wright R-975]] radial engine, one built.<ref name=\"Orbis\" />\n;C4-301\n:Variant with a 300hp (224kW) [[Pratt & Whitney Wasp Junior]]  radial engine, one built.<ref name=\"Orbis\" />\n\n==Specifications (C4-225) ==\n{{Aircraft specs\n|ref=Jane's all the World's Aircraft 1931<ref name=JAWA1931>{{cite book |title=Jane's all the World's Aircraft 1931 |editor1-last=Grey |editor1-first=C.G. |year=1931 |publisher=Sampson Low, Marston & company, ltd |location=London |pages=318c-319c}}</ref>\n|prime units?=imp\n<!--\n        General characteristics\n-->\n|crew=1 or 2\n|capacity=2 or 3 pax, (four seats total)\n|length ft=50\n|span ft=32\n|span in=3.75\n|height ft=9\n|wing area sqft=299\n|aspect ratio=<!-- sailplanes -->\n|airfoil=\n|empty weight lb=2325\n|gross weight lb=3515\n|max takeoff weight kg=\n|max takeoff weight lb=\n|max takeoff weight note=\n|fuel capacity=Fuel: {{cvt|85|USgal|impgal l}} in two wing tanks; Oil: {{cvt|6|USgal|impgal l}} \n|more general=\n<!--\n        Powerplant\n-->\n|eng1 number=1\n|eng1 name=[[Wright J-6]]\n|eng1 type=9-cylinder air-cooled radial piston engine\n|eng1 hp=240\n\n|prop blade number=2\n|prop name=fixed pitch steel propeller\n|prop dia m=<!-- propeller aircraft -->\n|prop dia ft=<!-- propeller aircraft -->\n|prop dia in=<!-- propeller aircraft -->\n|prop dia note=\n<!--\n        Performance\n-->\n|max speed mph=129.7\n|cruise speed mph=109\n|cruise speed note=</li>\n*'''Landing speed:''' {{cvt|51|mph|kn km/h}}\n|stall speed kmh=\n|stall speed mph=\n|stall speed kts=\n|stall speed note=\n|never exceed speed kmh=\n|never exceed speed mph=\n|never exceed speed kts=\n|never exceed speed note=\n|range km=\n|range miles=\n|range nmi=\n|range note=\n|ferry range km=\n|ferry range miles=\n|ferry range nmi=\n|ferry range note=\n|endurance=<!-- if range unknown -->\n|ceiling ft=15000\n|ceiling note=service\n|g limits=<!-- aerobatic -->\n|roll rate=<!-- aerobatic -->\n|climb rate ftmin=905\n|climb rate note=initial\n|time to altitude=\n|wing loading lb/sqft=11.7\n|fuel consumption kg/km=\n|fuel consumption lb/mi=\n|power/mass={{cvt|14.65|lb/hp|kg/kW}}\n|more performance=\n}}\n\n==See also==\n{{aircontent\n<!-- include as many lines are appropriate. additional lines/entries with carriage return. -->\n|see also=\n|related=<!-- related developments -->\n* [[Spartan C5]]\n|similar aircraft=<!-- similar or comparable aircraft -->\n|sequence=<!-- designation sequence, if appropriate -->\n|lists=<!-- related lists -->\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{commons category|Spartan Aircraft Company}}\n===Notes===\n{{r